defaultThe
default new approach to tax policy making
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.      be fair. The Committee accepts that not all commentators will agree on the detail of what constitutes a fair tax, but a tax system which is considered to be fu
defaultndamentally unfair will ultimately fail to command consent.
default&#xa0;
default2.      
defaultsupport
default growth and encourage competition.
default&#xa0;
default3.      
defaultprovide
default certainty. In virtually all circumstances the application of the tax rules 
defaultshould
default be certain. It should not normally be 
defaultnecessary for anyone to resort to the courts in order to resolve how the rules operate in relation to his or her tax affairs.
default&#xa0;
default4.      
defaultprovide
default stability. Changes to the underlying rules should be kept to a minimum and policy shocks should both be avoided. 
defaultThere should be a justifiable economic and/or social basis for any change to the tax rules and this justification should be made public and the underlying policy made clear.
default&#xa0;
default5.      The Committee also considers that it is important that a person's tax lia
defaultbility should be easy to calculate and straightforward and cheap to collect. To this end, tax policy should be practicable.
default&#xa0;
default6.      Finally, the tax system as a whole must be coherent. New provisions should complement the existing tax system, not conflict
default with it.
